**2024 Could Become the Hottest Year on Record, Warns OMM Report**
A World Meteorological Organization (OMM) report released during the COP29 in Baku, Azerbaijan, warns that 2024 could become the hottest year on record. The 'State of the Climate' document highlights that the decade of 2015-2024 is the warmest since records began. The global average temperature has exceeded previous values for 16 consecutive months, from June 2023 to September 2024. Between January and September 2024, the average air temperature was 1.54°C above the pre-industrial average, surpassing the critical threshold of the Paris Agreement. According to the report, the temporary increase is 'concerning' as it may put the Earth in a 'danger zone', but it is estimated that the long-term temperature rise will be around 1.3°C. The report also notes that 2023 saw a record level of greenhouse gas emissions, with a trend of increase expected in 2024. The content of heat in the oceans, responsible for absorbing about 90% of the global excess heat, has reached record levels. Additionally, the accelerated melting of glaciers contributes to the rise in sea level, which is now growing more than twice the rate observed between 1993 and 2002. The OMM emphasizes the urgency of taking action to mitigate climate change before the 1.5°C threshold is permanently exceeded. 'Each fraction of a degree of warming matters, as it intensifies extreme weather events and causes catastrophic losses,' the organization says. 'It is essential to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and improve climate adaptation strategies.'
