**Vilfand: Probability of 2024 Being the Warmest Year on Record Increases**
The probability of 2024 becoming the warmest year on record is increasing, according to Roman Vilfand, the scientific director of the Russian Hydrometeorological Center. 'The probability of 2024 being the warmest year is increasing. This is due to the fact that the 2023-2024 El Niño event was very intense, which led to an increase in sea surface temperature in mid-latitudes. The temperature of the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans is record-high for the entire period of observation, and this has been ongoing for 15 months. This transfer of heat from the ocean to the atmosphere is causing the global temperature to rise,' Vilfand explained. He noted that the main cause of warming is the increase in greenhouse gases, which prevent the long-wave radiation from the Earth's surface from being released. 'Currently, it is being delayed by this greenhouse gas, and its concentration is not decreasing, which is the main problem with warming,' he added. Vilfand also stated that, based on data from the World Meteorological Organization, 2024 is likely to be the first year when the average global temperature exceeds the pre-industrial period temperature norm by 1.5 degrees. 'This is a threshold value, it is marked in the Paris Agreement, we need to strive for the temperature increase not to exceed 1.5 degrees by the end of the century. Therefore, yes, this year is likely to be the warmest,' Vilfand explained.
