**Earth’s Land and Trees Absorbed Almost No Net Carbon in 2023**
A preliminary report shows that Earth's land-based carbon sinks, including forests, wetlands, and soil, absorbed almost no net carbon in 2023, the hottest year on record. This collapse of terrestrial carbon sinks is a concern, as it means the world's land-based ecosystems are losing their ability to regulate the planet's temperature and mitigate climate change. Johan Rockström, director of the Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, stated, 'Nature has so far balanced our abuse. This is coming to an end.' The collapse of terrestrial carbon sinks is provisional and may be due to excessive drought and wildfires caused by global heating. Without the planet's carbon sinks performing at a normal rate, reaching net zero will not be possible. Researchers say that carbon flow through the ocean and land is still a mystery, and climate models may be too optimistic due to missing factors such as drought-induced tree mortality. The planet's ability to absorb carbon weakening even moderately would make much steeper reductions in greenhouse gas emissions necessary to get to net zero.
